data.text: Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic wil âwill, desireâ + helm âhelmet, protectionâ. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the âconqueredâ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by John , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented.
